Overall, the participants showcased significantly improved performances with the robotic handles rather than with the standard instrument, with both the lower and upper quartiles of their box-plots scoring higher for the two novel handles. The mean completion rate, here defined as the arithmetic average percentage of rings that were successfully transferred from the one set of pegs to the other out of the total of 6 rings, between all 9 participants, and for each of the 3 devices is depicted in Fig. 5b. It is evident that the two handles clearly outperformed the standard instrument. Figure 5c shows the successful attempt rate, defined as the percentage of attempts out of the 10 attempts when a participant was able to transfer all 6 rings. Once again, we notice the same trend of the two handles being superior to the standard instrument that had a \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
